6
00:00:50.000 --> 00:01:02.000
So let's jump back into Maya one last time and look at a script from the latest release of the DNA calibration repository that allows us to build a rig with textures.

7
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Back inside of Maya, in the DNA calibration folder, you will find in the examples folder a script named DNAViewerBuildRigWithTextures.

8
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:20.000
This script allows users to generate a functional rig in Maya with applied textures.

9
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
The assets this uses are located in the data folder.

10
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:31.000
This script has already been configured to load the eta DNA file from the mh4 folder.

11
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:35.000
I have already assembled eta with Oliver Textures.

12
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:40.000
To use this script, ensure that DirectX11 has been enabled.

13
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:54.000
To do this, go to Preferences, Display, and then to Viewport 2.0 and ensure the rendering engine is set to DirectX11.

14
00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:07.000
In a new Python window, with the entire script pasted in here, ensure that you have assigned the path for the root directory pointing to the DNA calibration folder.

15
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:19.000
If you wish to use this with your own character, scroll down here and assign the paths for the DNA file and the maps folder.

16
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Then select this entire script and execute it.

17
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Now, let's review these steps before we move on.

18
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:41.000
The latest update of the DNA calibration repository includes support for Maya 2024 and the DNAViewerBuildRigWithTextures script located in the examples folder.

19
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:47.000
This script allows users to generate a functional rig with applied textures.

20
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
